Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while prior work has explored weakly supervised learning of event representations, most approaches either focus exclusively on text (Paper 1 and 2) or incorporate mental states within narratives (Paper 3), but none effectively bridge unpaired multimodal data—specifically text and vision—without explicit cross-modal alignment. The key challenge lies in grounding abstract semantic structures like events and their arguments (e.g., agent, patient, instrument) across modalities when no image-caption pairs are available. I propose leveraging *narrative consistency*—the idea that events unfold coherently over time in stories—and *role coherence*, which ensures that participants in events maintain semantically plausible roles across descriptions. By training separate encoders for textual narratives and visual sequences using a dual-stream architecture, we can exploit temporal structure and role continuity as weak supervisory signals. Crucially, this method does not require paired data; instead, it uses self-supervised contrastive objectives guided by narrative flow and argument-role plausibility derived from commonsense knowledge. Unlike Paper 1, which clusters events based on co-occurrence, my approach models structured argument roles and leverages inter-modal consistency through narrative logic. Compared to Paper 2’s attention-based re-contextualization, I go beyond token-level semantics to model full event schemas with typed arguments. And unlike Paper 3, which focuses on mental states in short texts, I extend such reasoning to cross-modal learning without paired annotations. This creates a novel pathway for learning rich, structured semantics from disjoint text and video corpora—an underexplored yet highly practical setting given the scarcity of aligned multimodal datasets.

